### Appendix A: Proof of Theorem 2.3 (Energy-Constrained Contraction)

*Proof*. Let $\mu, \nu$ be two distributions on $\mathcal{X}$. By the HWI inequality (Otto-Villani, 2000):

$$W_2(\mu, \nu)^2 \leq \frac{2}{\lambda} \left( H(\mu|\pi) + H(\nu|\pi) - 2H(P_\varepsilon\mu|\pi) \right)$$

where $\pi$ is the Gibbs measure $\pi(x) \propto e^{-\mathcal{E}(x)/T}$ and $H(\cdot|\pi)$ is relative entropy.

Since $\mathcal{E}$ is $\lambda$-strongly convex on $\mathcal{M}$, the Gibbs measure satisfies a log-Sobolev inequality with constant $\lambda/T$. The energy constraint $\mathcal{E}(x) \leq \varepsilon$ ensures that $P_\varepsilon$ maps to a subset where the log-Sobolev constant is preserved.

Applying the contraction property of the Gibbs sampler under log-Sobolev inequalities (Chewi et al., 2020), we obtain:

$$W_2(P_\varepsilon \mu, P_\varepsilon \nu) \leq \left(1 - \frac{\lambda \varepsilon}{T}\right) W_2(\mu, \nu)$$

∎

